  <h1>The new Income-tax Act 2025: what changes</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>7 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>The Income-tax Act 2025 replaces the Income-tax Act 1961 with effect from FY 2026-27, aiming to simplify and consolidate the law without large changes to tax rates.</b> It introduces a single 'tax year' concept, plainer drafting, and renumbered provisions, including TDS under Sections 392 (salary), 393 (non-salary) and 394 (TCS).</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">What the new Act is and is not</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">The 'tax year' concept</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">Renumbered TDS and TCS</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">What finance teams should do now</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">What the new Act is and is not</h2>
<p>The Income-tax Act 2025 is largely a <b>structural rewrite</b>: it removes redundant provisos and explanations, consolidates scattered sections, and uses simpler language and tables. It is <b>not</b> a wholesale change in tax policy &mdash; rates, regimes and most computational concepts continue. The bigger practical impact is renumbering and reorganisation, which affects every reference, software mapping and template a finance team uses.</p><div class="callout warn"><b>Caution.</b> Exact new-Act section numbers should be confirmed against the enacted text and notified rules. Where a mapping is uncertain, we flag it. <span class="verify">VERIFY new-Act section</span></div>

  <h2 id="s1">The 'tax year' concept</h2>
<p>The new Act replaces the dual <b>'previous year' and 'assessment year'</b> terminology with a single <b>'tax year'</b>. This removes a long-standing source of confusion for taxpayers, aligning the period of income with the year of reference. Returns, assessments and compliance will be described by the tax year.</p>

  <h2 id="s2">Renumbered TDS and TCS</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Provision</th><th>Old Act (1961)</th><th>New Act (2025)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>TDS on salary</td><td>Section 192</td><td>Section 392</td></tr><tr><td>TDS on non-salary payments</td><td>Sections 193-196 etc.</td><td>Section 393 (consolidated)</td></tr><tr><td>TCS</td><td>Section 206C</td><td>Section 394</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>See <a href="../numberiq-tds-chart-fy2026-27.html">the TDS chart</a> for the rate-and-section map. <span class="verify">VERIFY</span> exact sub-section references as rules are notified.</p>

  <h2 id="s3">What finance teams should do now</h2>
<ul><li>Re-map standard letters, notices, and engagement templates to new-Act references.</li><li>Update accounting/payroll software section masters for TDS/TCS.</li><li>Train teams on the tax-year terminology.</li><li>Keep a 1961-to-2025 concordance handy during the transition.</li></ul>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>When does the Income-tax Act 2025 take effect?</summary><p>From FY 2026-27. It replaces the Income-tax Act 1961, primarily simplifying and renumbering the law rather than changing rates and regimes.</p></details>
    <details><summary>What replaces 'previous year' and 'assessment year'?</summary><p>A single 'tax year' concept, which removes the earlier dual-year terminology and aligns the period of income with the year of reference.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Where do the old TDS sections go?</summary><p>Broadly, salary TDS moves to Section 392, non-salary TDS consolidates into Section 393, and TCS moves to Section 394; confirm exact sub-sections against the enacted text.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>The 2025 Act replaces the 1961 Act from FY 2026-27.</li><li>Mainly a simplification/renumbering, not a rate overhaul.</li><li>Single 'tax year' replaces previous year/assessment year.</li><li>TDS/TCS renumbered to Sections 392/393/394 — verify sub-sections.</li></ul>
  </div>

